This data depicts roads in and around Rocky Mountain National Park. It is derived and developed from a number of sources. These include: 1:100000-scale USGS Digital Line Graph (DLG) transportation data, the 1:50000-scale USGS map of Rocky Mountain National Park (40105-A4-PF-050), GPS (Global Positioning System) data, and heads-up digitizing using USGS DOQQ data as a backdrop. Common names have been added and the sources of individual vectors identified. See <URL:http://edcwww.cr.usgs.gov/nsdi/html/dlg100/dlg100> for more information concerning UGSG 100k DLG data. This link valid in July 1998. This data covers a 36 quad area centered on ROMO. The 7.5 minute USGS quads covered are: Clark Peak, Chambers Lake, Comanche Peak, Pingree Park, Crystal Mountain, Mount Richthofen, Fall River Pass, Trail Ridge, Estes Park, Glen Haven, Bowen Mountain, Grand Lake, McHenrys Peak, Longs Peak, Panorama Peak, Trail Mountain, Shadow Mountain, Isolation Peak, Allens Park, Raymond, Granby, Strawberry Lake, Monarch Lake, Ward, Gold Hill, Rawah Lakes, Boston Peak, Kinikinik, Rustic, Big Narrows, Poudre Park, Buckhorn Mountain, Drake, Pinewood Lake, Lyons, Boulder. Data used and/or developed by the Rocky Mountain National Park GIS Program is used in the protection and management of Rocky Mountain National Park. en

Horizontal accuracy varies depending on the source of individual components within the data. Data derived from USGS data (DLGs, DEMs, DOQQs) are assumed to meet National Map Accuracy standards, though extensive experience in using USGS data for the Rocky Mountain National Park area has shown that many data components have spatial errors exceeding the National Map Accuracy standards. Data produced from GPS (Global Positioning System) field data is assumed to be spatially accurate to within 2-5 meters.
19950101 A data layer consisting of 1:100000-scale USGS DLG transportation data was queried and vectors were extracted to form the base of this data. Additional vectors were added and some 1:100000-scale vectors were replaced with more accurate vectors digitized off of a paper copy of the 1:50000-scale USGS Rocky Mountain National Park Map (40105-A4-PF-050). Additional vectors were added and some 1:100000-scale and 1:50000-scale vectors were replaced with more accurate vectors created by collecting GPS data. Line data were collected using Trimble GPS (Global Positioning System) equipment. All data was post-processed with Trimble's software resulting in an accuracy of 2-5 meters. Line features were edited and splined to clean up vectors using the ARC/INFO ARCEDIT module. Attributes were added to vectors using the ARC/INFO ARCEDIT module and ARC/INFO TABLES commands, though some attributes were attached to the data in the field using a pre-defined data dictionary. See <URL:http://www.trimble.com> for additional information regarding the specifications of Trimble equipment. Presently (July 1998) Rocky Mountain National Park is using a Trimble Pathfinder Professional and Trimble GeoExplorer IIs to collect GPS data. Additionally, some vectors were added and others adjusted using heads-up digitizing technique (digitizing off of the computer screen) using 1:12000- scale USGS DOQQs as a backdrop. Additionally, some vectors were adjusted to fit in the rights of way as shown on digital parcel data received from the town of Estes Park and Larimer County, Colorado. Attributes were added to vectors using the ARC/INFO ARCEDIT module and ARC/INFO TABLES commands, though some attributes were attached to the data in the field using a pre-defined data dictionary when GPS data was collected.
